  1. Briefly describe what Bash commands zcat, zless, zmore, and zgrep do.

Answer: zcat lets users to display contents of compressed files, similar to cat it prints the contents out in the terminal.

zless allows users to view the contents of the compressed file, similar to the less command it opens file in the default text editor (Vi) for Ubuntu.

zmore is similar to zless but different in the user interface during navigation through the file, zless is more like scrolling while zmore is like reading documents one page at a time. It is all up to the userâs preference.

zgrep similar to grep, allows users to search for text/pattern within a compressed file.

  1. To compress, or not to compress. Thatâs the question. Letâs focus on the big data file labevents.csv.gz. Compare compressed gz file size to the uncompressed file size. Compare the run times of zcat < ~/mimic/labevents.csv.gz | wc -l versus wc -l labevents.csv. Discuss the trade off between storage and speed for big data files. (Hint: gzip -dk < FILENAME.gz > ./FILENAME. Remember to delete the large labevents.csv file after the exercise.)

Answer:

The bash code below ARE reproducible after regenerating labevents.csv file with gzip -dk hosp/labevents.csv.gz > hosp/labevents.csv. (Since removed after exercise done)

echo "File size of labevents.csv.gz and labevents.csv"
# $5 is file size while $9 shows the file, -h is human-readable format
ls -lh ~/mimic/hosp/labevents* | awk '{print $5, $9}'

echo "Run time of labevents.csv.gz"
# $5 is file size while $9 shows the file, -h is human-readable format
time ls -lh ~/mimic/hosp/labevents.csv.gz

echo "Run time of labevents.csv"
time ls -lh ~/mimic/hosp/labevents.csv

The storage difference is almost 10 times with 1.9Gb in .csv.gz and 13Gb in .csv while the run time penalty is minimum with 0.001s difference in real world time, so I would prefer to keep the big data files compressed in the .csv.gz format

Q4. Whoâs popular in Price and Prejudice

  1. You and your friend just have finished reading Pride and Prejudice by Jane Austen. Among the four main characters in the book, Elizabeth, Jane, Lydia, and Darcy, your friend thinks that Darcy was the most mentioned. You, however, are certain it was Elizabeth. Obtain the full text of the novel from http://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/42671/pg42671.txt and save to your local folder.
wget -nc -P ~/ http://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/42671/pg42671.txt

Explain what wget -nc does. Do not put this text file pg42671.txt in Git. Complete the following loop to tabulate the number of times each of the four characters is mentioned using Linux commands.

Answer: wget -nc downloads a file from the web and -nc is a flag to indicate that we do not want to overwrite existing file.

# -P indicates where to save the file
wget -nc -P ~/ http://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/42671/pg42671.txt

# -n allows for outputs to be on the same line
# -o only outputs the matched part and -w is matching the whole word
for char in Elizabeth Jane Lydia Darcy
do
  echo -n "$char: "
  grep -o -w $char ~/pg42671.txt | wc -l
done
  1. Whatâs the difference between the following two commands?
echo 'hello, world' > test1.txt

and

echo 'hello, world' >> test2.txt

Answer: The > will overwrite the file if it exists while >> will append/add the output to the file. So echo 'hello, world' > test1.txt test1.txt will only contain âhello, worldâ no matter what is originally had while echo 'hello, world' >> test2.txt will have âhello, worldâ attached at the end of what it originally have.

  1. Using your favorite text editor (e.g., vi), type the following and save the file as middle.sh:
#!/bin/sh
# Select lines from the middle of a file.
# Usage: bash middle.sh filename end_line num_lines
head -n "$2" "$1" | tail -n "$3"

Using chmod to make the file executable by the owner, and run

cd ~/biostat-203b_hw/hw1
./middle.sh ~/pg42671.txt 20 5

Explain the output. Explain the meaning of "$1", "$2", and "$3" in this shell script. Why do we need the first line of the shell script?

Answer: "$1", "$2", and "$3" refers to the first, second and third argument in the script execution, namely ~/pg42671.txt, 20 and 5 in this case based on their positions.

#!/bin/sh is used to indicate the interpreter to use to execute the script which in this case it is the path to the Bourne shell which is a compatible shell to run the script on. If we do not include the first row, the system would use the default shell to execute the script which lags clarity and may lead to output that user did not intent to have.

The output basically displays the last 5 lines of the first 20 lines of ~/pg42671.txt.
